<h2>Our AFSP Stories From 2017</h2>
<div class="ar17-map" id="map-2"></div>

<div class="ar17-section project2025-slide" id="ar17-project-2025">
<h2>Project 2025: Leading the Fight to Reduce the Suicide Rate</h2>
<div class="project2025-slide__content">
<div class="videoEmbed">
<iframe width="853" height="480" src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/246787591" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen=""></iframe>
</div>
<div class="project2025-statement">
<h3>The American Foundation for Suicide Prevention has set a bold goal to reduce the rate of suicide in the United States by the year 2025. We’ve launched <a href="https://afsp.org/campaigns/project-2025/" target="_blank">Project 2025</a> to help us attain that goal.</h3>
<p>Thanks to our investments in science, we know more about how to prevent suicide than ever before. Through collaborations with other organizations, accrediting bodies, professional associations, and leaders in other industry sectors, AFSP is focusing its prevention efforts on the kinds of programs, policies and interventions that will save the most lives in the shortest amount of time.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="ar17-section recognition-slide" id="ar17-recognition">
<h2>Recognizing Our 2017 Achievements</h2>
<div class="recognition-section">
<div class="recognition-images">
<img class="recognition-image" src="https://afsp.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/35535194686_cc3dc266de_o.jpg" alt="">
<img class="recognition-image" src="https://afsp.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/35406022732_03fedc035c_o.jpg" alt="">
<img class="recognition-image" src="https://afsp.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/35574007845_d4979fffdc_o.jpg" alt="">
</div>
<div class="recognition-copy">
<h3>Federal Advocacy Forum and Allies in Action</h3>
<p>The <a href="https://afsp.org/our-work/advocacy/advocacy-events/annual-advocacy-forum/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Annual Advocacy Forum</a> is AFSP’s largest effort to educate federal officials about mental health and suicide prevention. This past June, 230 volunteer advocates and staff from all 50 states joined us in our nation’s capital to ask all 535 members of Congress for their support on suicide prevention and mental health priorities.</p>
<p>Our keynote speakers for the event were former Senior White House officials <a href="https://afsp.org/david-axelrod-karl-rove-faceoff-discuss-mental-health-nations-largest-suicide-prevention-organization/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">David Axelrod and Karl Rove</a>, two men from both sides of the aisle who discussed their personal experiences with suicide loss.</p>
<p>We also took the opportunity to recognize leaders in suicide prevention public policy at our annual Allies in Action awards ceremony. The following awardees were honored:</p>
<ul>
<li>Catherine Barber (Lifetime Achievement Award)</li>
<li>Joe Dunn, Office of Senator Christopher Murphy (Congressional Staff Award)</li>
<li>Brenda Destro, Office of Senator Bill Cassidy (Congressional Staff Award)</li>
<li>Carrie Palmer Swope, Office of Representative Eddie Bernice Johnson (Congressional Staff Award)</li>
<li>Representative Eddie Bernice Johnson (Congressional Award)</li>
<li><a href="https://afsp.org/missouri-residents-honor-senator-jill-schupp-leadership-making-suicide-prevention-priority/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Missouri Senator Jill Schupp (Allies in Action State Award)</a></li>
<li>Alaska Senator Lyman Hoffman (Allies in Action State Award)</li>
<li>Karl Rosston — Montana (Allies in Action State Award)</li>
<li><a href="https://afsp.org/local-little-rock-hero-recognized-national-award-work-advocating-suicide-prevention/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Tyler West — Arkansas</a></li>
<li>Eric Tash — Hawai’i</li>
<li><a href="https://afsp.org/missouri-hero-recognized-national-award-suicide-prevention-advocacy/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Linda Fehrmann — Missouri</a></li>
<li><a href="https://afsp.org/alaskan-hero-recognized-national-award-suicide-prevention-advocacy/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Jim Biela — Alaska</a></li>
</ul>
<p>Want to see more from our Chapter Leadership Conference? <a href="https://www.flickr.com/photos/afsp/albums/72157685585255035" target="_blank" rel="noopener">View more photos.</a></p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="recognition-section">
<div class="recognition-copy">
<h3>Chapter Leadership Conference</h3>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">The fight to stop suicide starts in our communities, at the ground level. </span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">AFSP’s chapters carry out our mission locally. Led by people who live in and know the needs of each area, our chapter volunteers help us deliver education and prevention programs to schools and businesses, provide caring support to survivors of suicide loss, advocate for smart public policy, and organize events to raise awareness and funds for suicide prevention. </span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">Nothing we do would be possible without our chapter volunteers. Organized around the theme of 30 Years Strong, </span><span class="s2">AFSP’s Chapter Leadership Conference, held in Irvine, California recognized the milestones AFSP accomplished toward its mission to save lives and bring hope to those affected by suicide. </span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s2">The three-day event enabled staff and volunteers from each of our 85 chapters to gather, share their experiences, and learn and be inspired by each other, as we looked forward to the year ahead.</span></p>
<p>Want to see more from our Chapter Leadership Conference? <a href="https://www.flickr.com/photos/afsp/albums/72157675870603064" target="_blank" rel="noopener">View more photos.</a></p>
</div>
<div class="recognition-images">
<img class="recognition-image" src="https://afsp.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/32368685472_814a0453fe_o.jpg" alt="">
<img class="recognition-image" src="https://afsp.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/32368689952_6a2ed40333_o.jpg" alt="">
<img class="recognition-image" src="https://afsp.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/31677181144_c1f5dcc12a_o.jpg" alt="">
</div>
</div>
<div class="recognition-section">
<div class="recognition-images">
<img class="recognition-image" src="https://afsp.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/34617263645_cfdd3ee502_o.jpg" alt="">
<img class="recognition-image" src="https://afsp.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/33807328963_2fa0c54bde_o.jpg" alt="">
<img class="recognition-image" src="https://afsp.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/33774266444_53b95daef5_o.jpg" alt="">
</div>
<div class="recognition-copy">
<h3>Lifesavers Gala</h3>
<p><a href="https://afsp.org/29th-annual-lifesavers-gala/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">The 29th Annual Lifesavers Gala</a> was an inspiring night commemorating AFSP’s 30 years together, and featuring distinguished guests and honorees who have dedicated themselves to suicide prevention.</p>
<p>The evening was hosted by actor and comedian Chris Gethard, whose acclaimed one-man show and HBO special <em>Career Suicide</em> recounted his own personal experience with suicidal thoughts, and chaired by Kabir Nath, President &amp; CEO, Otsuka North America Pharmaceutical Business Division Otsuka America, Inc.</p>
<p>Throughout the night, Gethard spoke touchingly – yet with quite a bit of humor – about his personal and professional journey of having opened up about his struggles with mental health, and how no one should feel hesitant to reach out for help.</p>
<p>This year’s Gala, held in in New York City at Jazz at Lincoln Center’s Appel Room, raised more than $530,000 for the fight against suicide.</p>
<p>The night featured remarks from the following award winners:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Research Award Winner Dr. Joan Asarnow</strong>, who has dedicated her career to developing, testing, and implementing evidence-based treatments for adolescents at risk for suicide in emergency department and primary care settings</li>
<li><strong>Survivor Award Winner Allison Schmitt</strong>, an eight-time Olympic medal swimmer and three-time Olympian who lost her cousin to suicide and has now devoted her time and energy to being vocal about her loss and her own experiences with depression</li>
<li><strong>Public Service Award Winner Instagram</strong>, presented by Elyse Fox, founder of the popular online community <a href="https://www.instagram.com/sadgirlsclub/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Sad Girls Club</a>, and accepted by Instagram’s global head of marketing Cliff Hopkins, who spoke of the new tools introduced to the app this year that help connect those in need with help</li>
</ul>
<p>Want to see more from the Lifesavers Gala? <a href="https://www.flickr.com/photos/afsp/albums/72157681831692570" target="_blank" rel="noopener">View more photos.</a></p>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="story" id="research_swann">
<div class="left-panel">
<h3>About AFSP Research Grants</h3>
<p class="p1"><strong><span class="s1">In 2017, AFSP invested a total of $4.65 Million Dollars in 27 new research grants. </span></strong><span class="s1">AFSP is the largest private funder of suicide research. Our Scientific Council helps set the national research agenda. </span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">Of those grants, two are Focus Grants, totaling nearly $2 million.</span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">Over the past 5 years, AFSP has awarded $18.8 million. </span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">Over the past 10 years, AFSP has awarded $26.5 million.</span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1"><a href="http://afsp.org/our-work/research/research-grants/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">AFSP’s research grants</a> cover a broad range of categories including: </span></p>
<p class="p3"><span class="s1"><b>NEUROBIOLOGICAL: </b>How do brain structure and neurochemical function contribute to suicide?</span></p>
<p class="p3"><span class="s1"><b>PSYCHOSOCIAL: </b>What are the risk factors and warning signs for suicide?</span></p>
<p class="p3"><span class="s1"><b>GENETIC: </b>What genetic pathways are associated with suicide risk, and can we develop biological interventions and treatments?</span></p>
<p class="p3"><span class="s1"><b>TREATMENT: </b>What treatments — like therapies and medications — are effective at reducing suicide?</span></p>
<p class="p3"><span class="s1"><b>COMMUNITY: </b>What universal prevention programs — like hotlines, gatekeeper training, and community-based programs — are the most effective?</span></p>
<p class="p4"><span class="s1"><b>LOSS SURVIVORS: </b>What is the impact of suicide loss, and what helps the healing process?</span></p>
</div>
<div class="right-panel">
<h3>Volunteer Spotlight</h3>
<h4>Research Study: Behavioral Mechanisms, Prediction, and Treatment of Short-Term Suicide Risk</h4>
<img src="https://afsp.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/Swann-Alan-2-2016-1.jpg?w=1080" alt="">
<p class="p3"><span class="s2">Over the past 40 years, research has shown that lithium can help to reduce suicide risk… but we don’t yet know how. <a href="http://afsp.org/our-work/research/research-grants/behavioral-mechanisms-prediction-treatment-short-term-suicide-risk/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">The following study</a> seeks to determine if cognitive and behavioral factors associated with suicide, such as decision making, aggression and impulsiveness, change with lithium treatment. </span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s2">Dr. Alan Swann of Baylor College of Medicine in Houston, Texas has always been interested in finding practical approaches to treat severe clinical problems. During his residency, he studied mood disorders and the mechanisms that activate human behavior. During this time, he developed a particular interest in the interaction between two seemingly opposite states: mania and depression. </span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s2">The combination of these two states, which can fluctuate rapidly, is associated with an increased risk for suicide. Parallel to developing this interest, Dr. Swann had the opportunity to research lithium in relation to mood disorders, studying its effects on brain function and aggressive behavior. Soon afterward, he collaborated in a clinical study of people who had survived self-inflicted gunshot wounds. This led him to the finding that impulsive behavior was related to feelings of hopelessness. </span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s2">Impulsivity, Swann discovered, increased the likelihood that someone would go through with a planned suicide attempt. Certain measures of impulsivity were elevated in people with bipolar disorder who had made potentially lethal suicide attempts. This was true whether the attempts were classified as “impulsive” or “premeditated.” Interestingly, participants in the study of self-inflicted gunshot wounds reported that the immediate precipitant of their suicide attempt was often a relatively minor stressor. Severe suicidal behavior appeared to be a combination of long-term factors and immediate regulation of behavior associated with stressors. </span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s2">While it is widely held that lithium can reduce suicide mortality through its effects on aggression and/or impulsivity, such effects have never been demonstrated using quantitative behavioral or physiological measures. As the recipient of one of this year’s two coveted AFSP Focus Grants – targeted, innovative, and potentially high impact studies that seek to inform and even transform suicide prevention efforts – Dr. Swann will be further studying the underlying mechanisms that change with f lithium treatment that makes it effective for short-term suicide risk. </span></p>
</div>
<i class="fa fa-times-circle ar17-close" aria-hidden="true"></i>
</div>

<h3>About AFSP Research Grants</h3>
<p class="p1"><strong><span class="s1">In 2017, AFSP invested a total of $4.65 Million Dollars in 27 new research grants. </span></strong><span class="s1">AFSP is the largest private funder of suicide research. Our Scientific Council helps set the national research agenda.</span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">Of those grants, two are Focus Grants, totaling nearly $2 million.</span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">Over the past 5 years, AFSP has awarded $18.8 million. </span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">Over the past 10 years, AFSP has awarded $26.5 million.</span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1"><a href="http://afsp.org/our-work/research/research-grants/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">AFSP’s research grants</a> cover a broad range of categories including: </span></p>

<div class="right-panel">
<h3>Volunteer Spotlight</h3>
<h4>Research Study: Using Nitrous Oxide to Treat Suicidal Ideation in Depressed Hospitalized Patients</h4>
<img src="https://afsp.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/Conway-Charles-2016.jpg?w=1080" alt="">
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">Imagine if there were treatment that could be used in emergency departments and inpatient units that rapidly reduced suicide risk, had few side effects and was safe and available for most people with suicidal ideation and behavior. </span></p>
<p class="p3"><span class="s1">Dr. Charles Conway has been working with his team at the Washington University School of Medicine to study treatment-resistant major depression – or TRMD – for many years. TRMD is the most severe form of depression, and the leading cause of suicide. An estimated 15 percent of those suffering with TRMD die by suicide. </span></p>
<p class="p3"><span class="s1">Recently his team, in collaboration Dr. Peter Nagele from the Department of Anesthesia at Washington University, conducted a study using nitrous oxide – known colloquially as “laughing gas” – in a group of individuals with TRMD. Within that study, they were able to demonstrate that nitrous oxide was effective in lowering depressive symptoms. Among the symptoms, suicidal thinking underwent the greatest change. </span></p>
<p class="p3"><span class="s1">From that study, the idea emerged to specifically target suicidal thinking using this treatment in hospitalized patients with acute suicidal ideation. <a href="http://afsp.org/our-work/research/research-grants/adjunctive-nitrous-oxide-acute-suicidal-ideation-unipolar-depressed-hospitalized-patients/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Dr. Conway is the recipient of one of this year’s two coveted AFSP Focus Grants</a>: targeted, innovative, and potentially high impact studies that seek to inform and even transform suicide prevention efforts. </span></p>
<p class="p3"><span class="s1">The project has great significance to Dr. Conway’s team, several of whom are motivated through their firsthand experience of the extreme pain and suffering associated with the loss of a loved one by suicide. It is Dr. Conway’s hope that this study will provide evidence of nitrous oxide’s usefulness in reducing suicidal thinking…a finding that could potentially revolutionize the field of suicide prevention.</span></p>
</div>
<i class="fa fa-times-circle ar17-close" aria-hidden="true"></i>
</div>

<div class="right-panel">
<h3>Volunteer Spotlight</h3>
<h4>Research Study: Safety Planning Intervention to Reduce Short-Term Risk (or, A Tale of Two Researchers)</h4>
<img src="https://afsp.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/brown-stanley_960x480.jpg?w=1080" alt="">
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">Imagine if there were a simple, personalized plan that helped people deal with suicidal thoughts and behavior as they emerged…so they could save their lives, rather than take their lives. </span></p>
<p class="p2"><span class="s1">Sometimes, the meeting of two great minds seems a matter of fate…though in this case, AFSP may have played a role in making it happen. Dr. Gregory K. Brown, Director of the Center for the Prevention of Suicide in the Department of Psychiatry at the Perelman School of Medicine of the University of Pennsylvania, first met Dr. Barbara Stanley, Director of the Suicide Intervention Center in the Department of Psychiatry at Columbia University, in 2004 when AFSP sponsored a collaborative, multi-site research project on the detection and classification of suicidal behaviors in emergency departments. That study provided important data involved with the Columbia Suicide Severity Rating Scale, which is now widely used for detecting suicidal ideation and behavior in both research and practice settings. They, along with Dr. Glenn Currier, from the University of Rochester (currently chair of psychiatry at University of South Florida), received the 2009 AFSP Research Award for their work assessing suicide risk in three emergency departments. </span></p>
<p class="p2"><span class="s1">Now, Drs. Brown and Stanley are working together again, as the recipients of an AFSP Focus Grant on Safety Planning to Reduce Short Term Risk. The study will examine the effectiveness of the Safety Planning Intervention (SPI) in emergency departments. SPI is a tool that provides those experiencing suicidal ideation with a specific set of concrete strategies to help decrease the risk of suicidal behavior. <span class="Apple-converted-space">  </span>It was initially used to help adolescents manage their suicidal behavior while waiting for medication in a treatment study, and later for reducing suicide risk among veterans seeking treatment at the Veterans Health Administration.</span></p>
<p class="p2"><span class="s1">It is Brown and Stanley’s mutual hope that using the simple Safety Plan, which involves patients working together with their treatment provider to recognize their own warning signs and coping strategies, and establishing when and who to reach out to for help, can be a tool for saving lives for those who are seen in the emergency departments for suicidal ideation and behavior.</span></p>
<div class="videoEmbed"><iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/f4dYmWxAK_Q?rel=0" width="560" height="315" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen"></iframe></div>

<div class="right-panel">
<h3>Volunteer Spotlight</h3>
<h4>Research Study: Using Mobile Technology to Reduce Suicide Risk in Physicians</h4>
<img src="https://afsp.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/guille-sen_960x543.jpg?w=1080" alt="">
<p class="p1"><span class="s2">This year, AFSP awarded Drs. Constance Guille of the Medical University of South Carolina and Srijan Sen of the University of Michigan a Linked Standard Research Grant for $300,000 to study the use of mobile technology to reduce suicide risk in physicians. Many don’t realize that <a href="https://afsp.org/our-work/education/physician-medical-student-depression-suicide-prevention/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><span class="s3">physicians have higher rates of burnout, depressive symptoms, and suicide risk than the general population</span></a>, and suicide ideation among training physicians and interns is on the rise. It’s estimated that one physician dies by suicide every day and very few seek mental health treatment. </span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s2"><a href="http://afsp.org/quilt_square/april-white/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">The study</a> evaluates the use of Cognitive Behavior Therapy (CBT) delivered via mobile technology, with medical interns providing daily ratings of mood via a mobile app, and receiving feedback about factors that may be contributing to their worsening of mood. Interns receive recommendations for engaging the CBT app during times of worsening ratings, which are measured using well-validated suicide rating scales. These results will be compared to interns in usual clinical care. </span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s2">The use of mobile technologies in providing support may represent a critical gap – and an essential next step – in the reduction of suicide in training physicians, as it breaks down common barriers to support such as time, convenience, acceptability, and problem management. If successful, the results of the study could have a rippling effect in delivering effective care to the general population.</span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s2">Dr. Sen is a shining example of AFSP’s cultivation of researchers over time. In 2009 he was the recipient of AFSP’s Young Investigator Grant, for <a href="http://afsp.org/tackling-high-rates-depression-suicidal-ideation-medical-interns-part-1-3/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">a study that demonstrated medical interns often develop increased rates of depressed mood and suicidal ideation during their first three months of internship</a>. In that earlier study, Dr. Sen also established that interns are willing to use web-based mobile interventions to help with depression. </span></p>
</div>
<i class="fa fa-times-circle ar17-close" aria-hidden="true"></i>

<div class="story" id="community_skurtu">
<div class="left-panel">
<h3>About Out of the Darkness Community Walks</h3>
<div class="videoEmbed"><iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/zmjmr1pt3KE?rel=0" width="560" height="315" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen"></iframe></div>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">Many people affected by suicide first learn of AFSP through the Out of the Darkness Walks. When the walks first began in 2004, few people attended.</span><strong><span class="s1"> This year, over 260,000 people participated in </span><span class="s2">over 550 </span><span class="s1">walks across the country. </span></strong></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">The Out of the Darkness Walks are AFSP’s largest fundraising effort, and this year was no exception, with over $22 million raised for research, education, advocacy, and support programs.</span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">The core of the Out of the Darkness Walks, the Community Walks created a movement. Held in hundreds of cities across the country, they give people the courage to open up about their own struggle or loss, and the platform to change our culture’s approach to mental health. This year we held over 400 walks, covering all 50 states and raised $</span><span class="s1">17.5M with more than 280,000 individuals walking or donating to the cause.</span></p>
<p class="p1">
</div>
<div class="right-panel">
<h3>Volunteer Spotlight</h3>
<h4>Bringing Suicide Prevention to the Prison Community</h4>
<img src="https://afsp.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/DSCN3448.jpg?w=1080" alt="">
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">This past May, AFSP’s Oregon chapter held the first ever <a href="https://afsp.donordrive.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=cms.page&amp;id=1196&amp;eventGroupID=9AA117B3-F522-BB6D-359D1AA2D75A7958" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><span class="s2">Out of the Darkness Walk</span></a> in the country to take place inside a state prison, at Santaim Correctional Institution. </span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">The walk was sponsored in conjunction with the Salem, Oregon Community Walk, and preceded a day before by an AFSP Talk Saves Lives™ education program, with 97 inmates – almost 25 percent of the entire inmate population – in attendance. </span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">A report published recently by the U.S Department of Justice revealed that people incarcerated in state prisons died by suicide at a rate of 20 per 100,000 in 2014 … an increase of 30 percent from the previous year.</span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">Adults in custody, as well as prison staff, together raised a combined $3,163 dollars for suicide prevention. The walk was organized by George Skurtu, an inmate whose father died by suicide, and who was released from custody just a few short weeks after the walk.</span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">&#8220;In January of 2010, at the age of 22, I was arrested. Six months later, I was sentenced to 90 months in prison in the state of Oregon.</span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">&#8220;During my incarceration, I decided prison wasn’t the legacy I wanted to leave behind. </span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">&#8220;Looking back at my life, I realized how much suicide had affected my life.</span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">&#8220;In 1990, when I was two years old and my sister was seven, my father, Ronald Skurtu, died by suicide. Growing up, I was oblivious to how my father died. One day, when I was about 16, my older sister randomly said, ‘I think you are old enough to know now. Dad didn’t die in a car accident. He died by suicide.’</span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">&#8220;Finding out what really happened to my father left me confused, but it never occurred to me to seek out counsel or support. For years, I carried around the weight of these feelings and did not talk about them. </span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">&#8220;I realized that my purpose was to help with suicide prevention efforts and provide support to those left behind by suicide. </span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">&#8220;I was told about AFSP’s <a href="https://afsp.donordrive.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=cms.page&amp;id=1196&amp;eventGroupID=9AA117B3-F522-BB6D-359D1AA2D75A7958" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><span class="s2">Community Walks</span></a> by a staff member. Watching an <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RklzTqwqVd8" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><span class="s2">Out of the Darkness Walks video</span></a> online and realizing how many people are affected by suicide, I broke down and cried in my supervisor’s office. I wrote a proposal, presented it to management of the facility, and organized the event.</span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">&#8220;I have found great purpose and fulfillment in helping others who have been affected by mood disorders, depression, incarceration, and suicide, just as I have been affected. This is the gift I am giving back.&#8221;</span></p>
<p><img class="size-large wp-image-16699 alignnone" src="http://afsp.imgix.net/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/DSCN3585.jpg?w=1024&amp;h=1024&amp;auto=format%2Cenhance" alt="" srcset="https://afsp.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/DSCN3585.jpg 5152w, https://afsp.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/DSCN3585-300x225.jpg 300w, https://afsp.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/DSCN3585-768x576.jpg 768w, https://afsp.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/DSCN3585-1024x768.jpg 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 5152px) 100vw, 5152px" /></p>
</div>
<i class="fa fa-times-circle ar17-close" aria-hidden="true"></i>
</div>
<div class="story" id="campus_deubel">
<div class="left-panel">
<h3>About Out of the Darkness Campus Walks</h3>
<div class="videoEmbed"><iframe src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/233365676" width="560" height="315" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen"></iframe></div>
<p>High school and college students across the country help raises awareness among their peers and local communities through AFSP’s Campus Walks, the fastest growing of AFSP’s walk events.</p>
<p><strong>Nearly 30,000 people participated in Campus Walks this year alone, </strong>helping to foster an understanding of understanding, support and healing, and representing the future of mental health and suicide prevention.</p>
</div>
<div class="right-panel">
<h3>Volunteer Spotlight</h3>
<h4>Walking on Campus at Suffolk County Community College</h4>
<img src="https://afsp.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/campus-walk-2017.2.jpg?w=1080" alt="">
<p>Anne Deubel is a 20-year-old student who has been participating in AFSP’s <u>Out of the Darkness Walks</u> since she was 14 years old. This year she organized the first ever Campus Walk on Long Island.</p>
<p><strong>How did you first get involved with AFSP? </strong></p>
<p>I truly believe it was an act of fate. When I was 14, I received a Facebook message from a family friend who was attending the 2011 Out of the Darkness Community Walk near me in Long Island. I attended to catch up with them. I was so inspired by the experience, that I reached out to my local chapter, and joined the committee to help plan the following walk!</p>
<p>It was during this time, as I became more educated about mental health, that I began to identify some of the common warning signs in my own thought processes – something I had experienced since I was younger. After a conversation with an older cousin, who received her PhD in developmental psychology, I began receiving treatment and learning coping skills throughout high school and college.</p>
<p><strong>How did your involvement shift from helping to organize the walks to becoming a board member of the Long Island chapter? </strong></p>
<p>Two years ago, I lost my aunt to mental illness. Already being involved with AFSP, I was surrounded by understanding and support. It also infused my volunteer work for AFSP with even more meaning. So my commitment to AFSP naturally grew.</p>
<p>I was invited to AFSP’s Chapter Leadership Conference, a once-a-year event in which volunteers and staff come together from across the country to share their experiences and learn how to have the most impact on their communities. That level of trust empowered me with confidence about my potential.</p>
<p>As a board member now for the Long Island chapter, my responsibilities include volunteer engagement and coordination, small third-party events, social media, and campus walks. I also speak at events sometimes as well about my own personal experience.</p>
<p><strong>This past year, you organized the first ever Campus Walk on Long Island. What inspired you to make that happen? </strong></p>
<p>I was in my second year as a student at Suffolk County Community College. I had done a group project for one of my [psychology?] classes in which I identified psychological stressors that were unique to many community college students, and needed to propose a solution. Naturally, I decided to plan an AFSP Campus Walk for my own school!</p>
<p>I was hoping in arranging for the Campus Walk to show other students that they are not alone in their struggle, and expose them to mental health education and help-seeking behaviors.</p>
<p><strong>What actually went into setting up and organizing the walk? Were there any particular challenges?</strong></p>
<p>My first step was visiting the counseling center. I knew they had an interest in helping students who struggled and encouraging positive mental health. We met once a week, figuring out which forms the campus would require: fundraising forms, speaker forms, meetings with security, approval from the grounds…it was a lot more than I was expecting! I also partnered with the Honors Club, which helped me set up training for our volunteers.</p>
<p><strong>How did the event go? </strong></p>
<p>We were really astounded by the turnout – over 200 walkers – and we raised over $11,000!</p>
<p>Being able to reach a community closer to Eastern Long Island was a big deal for us – the closest Community Walk is over an hour drive from the campus. Introducing AFSP to the community and giving a platform for suicide prevention truly was impactful.</p>
<p><strong>What’s next? Do you hope to organize more walks in the community? </strong></p>
<p>Right now, my major goal is to focus on the Campus Walks. We have a LOT of colleges in the area, and I would love to have an event on most (dare I say all?) campuses.</p>
<p><strong>What personal meaning does your work with AFSP have for you, in light of how you first became involved and anything you’ve experience since? </strong></p>
<p>When I began volunteering, I thought it would be a thing I would do with the spare time between clubs in high school. If you asked me about suicide 10 years ago, you would have been met with a blank stare. My involvement with AFSP has allowed me to become a more empathetic person in a very cynical world. It has empowered me in regard to my own mental health. It has given me an understanding support system in the wake of loss.</p>
<p>I’ve decided this is going to be my future in some way. I’m considering going into research, particularly in the field of neurology. The brain is an astounding organ impacting so much of our quality of life – it deserves more intense research and expansion.</p>
</div>
<i class="fa fa-times-circle ar17-close" aria-hidden="true"></i>

<div class="story" id="advocacy_biela">
<div class="left-panel">
<h3>About State Capitol Days</h3>
<p><strong>This year, State Capitol Day events were held in 32 states, up from 22 last year. Our voices are being heard: lawmakers passed and signed into law 13 state bills that AFSP had highlighted as top priorities at our State Capitol Day events.</strong></p>
<p>The annual <a href="http://afsp.org/our-work/advocacy/advocacy-events/state-capitol-days/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">AFSP State Capitol Days</a> bring advocates together to educate public officials about suicide prevention and discuss how legislators can help to reduce suicide in their states and communities.</p>
<p>This year, AFSP volunteers successfully advocated for passage of 4 new school suicide prevention laws.  A total of 27 states require suicide prevention training for school personnel, and now 15 states require school districts to have suicide prevention, intervention, and postvention policies in place.</p>
<p>In addition, AFSP volunteers successfully advocated for passage of 5 new laws increasing awareness of and access to suicide prevention and mental health resources on college and university campuses and 7 state bills to expand suicide prevention programming and crisis line access statewide.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
</div>
<div class="right-panel">
<h3>Volunteer Spotlight</h3>
<h4>Suicide Prevention in Alaska</h4>
<img src="https://afsp.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/Senator-Hoffman-sponsor-of-State-Cap-Day.jpg?w=1080" alt="">
<p>Jim Biela works as a school social worker in rural Native Alaskan villages. He has been involved with AFSP since 2009. This year, he brought advocates to Juneau for Alaska’s first AFSP State Capitol Day, a three-day-long event which included individual meetings with legislators, the governor and lieutenant governor, as well as a presentation of AFSP’s <em>Talk Saves Lives</em>™ education program, which was broadcast across the state. He was named AFSP’s Field Advocate of the Year.</p>
<p>Here, he tells us about his remarkable efforts to bring suicide prevention to his unique community.</p>
<p><strong>When did you first move to Alaska? </strong></p>
<p>I moved to Bethel, Alaska in 2003.  Bethel is located in the southwest part of Alaska – 400 air miles from Anchorage.  We measure by air miles because the only way to get to Bethel is by air. There are no roads to the southwest.  Bethel is the hub village of 56 surrounding villages where populations range from 100 to 700 Alaskan Natives – also known as Yupik. The school district I work for as an itinerant school social worker has 26 villages and is roughly the size of West Virginia. I am assigned to six remote villages, on different islands, five of which are on the coast of the Bering Sea.</p>
<p>The only way to the villages is by air. Once the plane lands on the dirt airstrip, I get into either a boat, snow machine, or ATV to get to the school. I am usually in the villages for a period of four to six days.  There are no hotels, so I live in the schools. I purchased a sleeping bag and cot for each of my sites.</p>
<p><img class="size-large wp-image-19590 aligncenter" src="http://afsp.imgix.net/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/travel-from-one-village-to-antoher-on-Nelson-Island_n.jpg?w=1024&amp;h=1024&amp;auto=format%2Cenhance" alt="" srcset="https://afsp.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/travel-from-one-village-to-antoher-on-Nelson-Island_n.jpg 960w, https://afsp.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/travel-from-one-village-to-antoher-on-Nelson-Island_n-300x170.jpg 300w, https://afsp.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/travel-from-one-village-to-antoher-on-Nelson-Island_n-768x434.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 960px) 100vw, 960px" /></p>
<p>Winters can be bad here. The coldest winter was -70 with wind-chill. The snow was so high that if you walked outside, you would be walking on top of houses. The schools are the only buildings in the village that have running water or hot showers. Most of the villagers will come to take a maqii (hot steam).</p>
<p>I have worked in these communities long enough that I get invited to people’s homes for native food, which includes seal soup, moose stew, bird soup, and reindeer chili. The folks here are dependent on subsistence hunting, so fresh meat from moose, caribou, reindeer, seal, or even whale is often served. I have grown to love the food.</p>
<p>I attend tribal meetings to give updates on issues the tribal leaders may not know of. I also hold village gatherings to present on topics that the community would like to hear. Most of the time it is a suicide prevention presentation.</p>
<p><strong>How did you first get involved in AFSP? </strong></p>
<p>On April 28, 2009 my friend Cang died by suicide. After his death I wanted to do more for suicide prevention. I started an AFSP chapter here in Alaska. In March of 2010, I was invited to attend my first AFSP Advocacy Forum in Washington D.C. While at the event, I was able to mingle and talk to lawmakers about the large number of suicides here in Alaska.</p>
<p><strong>What kind of special considerations come into play for suicide prevention in Alaska? </strong></p>
<p><img class="size-large wp-image-19591 aligncenter" src="http://afsp.imgix.net/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/waiting-for-the-plane-in-village-.jpg?w=1024&amp;h=1024&amp;auto=format%2Cenhance" alt="" srcset="https://afsp.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/waiting-for-the-plane-in-village-.jpg 960w, https://afsp.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/waiting-for-the-plane-in-village--300x225.jpg 300w, https://afsp.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/waiting-for-the-plane-in-village--768x576.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 960px) 100vw, 960px" /></p>
<p>Since Bethel is the hub of 56 villages, the hospital is here. The villages have clinics, but budget cuts have forced them to lay off most of the behavioral health aides. There are no mental health workers in the villages. Insurance for mental health is complicated. We do referrals, but the person has to fly into Bethel for the initial intake, and neither Medicaid nor the local Denali insurance will cover the first trip.</p>
<p>When prescribed medication has run out in the village, it can take up to 7-14 days to get them refilled and sent by air. In addition, the Native culture does not believe in medication for mental health, and often parents take their children off the medication upon their return.</p>
<p><strong>Could you give us a brief overview of your work for AFSP in Alaska? </strong></p>
<p>Our district is unique; the school board had mandated for social workers to present to all 7-12<sup>th</sup> graders on suicide prevention every year. I was able to adjust that to twice a year. We alternate between different AFSP education presentations, such as <em>Talk Saves Lives</em>™ and <em>More Than Sad</em>.</p>
<p>I invited AFSP’s Vice President of Research, Dr. Jill Harkavy-Friedman to come to Alaska. She was introduced to families who talked to her about mental health in rural Alaska. She learned a lot of what a village in rural Alaska is like and the obstacles we face out here.</p>
<p>I started the first Survivor Day event here in Toksook Bay 2013. The outpouring of help from the student government was great. I advised them that I wanted to honor their culture and traditions while getting across a message of hope and healing. The student government made up posters by hand and put them up at the post office and the two small stores we have in the village. Letters were hand-delivered to each home in both English and Yupik. The day of the event, we flew in an interpreter for the elders.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>The event followed a memorial feast, where families brought in food for the buffet – salmon, seal soup, walrus, bird soup, moose stew, akutaq (Yupik ice cream)…in addition to pizza and spaghetti.</p>
<p>Following the memorial feast, traditional dancers performed Yuraq, a traditional Eskimo-style dancing performed to songs in Yupik. The dance is performed as a way of celebrating life.</p>
<p><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-19593" src="http://afsp.imgix.net/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/Yuraq-yupik-dance.jpg?w=1024&amp;h=1024&amp;auto=format%2Cenhance" alt="" srcset="https://afsp.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/Yuraq-yupik-dance.jpg 4288w, https://afsp.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/Yuraq-yupik-dance-300x199.jpg 300w, https://afsp.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/Yuraq-yupik-dance-768x510.jpg 768w, https://afsp.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/Yuraq-yupik-dance-1024x680.jpg 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 4288px) 100vw, 4288px" /></p>
<p>After that first year, we have continued to host the annual Survivor Day event in Toksook Bay, and it has now spread to other villages. We have even arranged for Yugtun (Yupik language) closed-captioning for AFSP’s Survivor Day film, <em>The Journey</em>. This is difficult, since some English words do not exist in Yugtun.</p>
<p><strong>Tell us about your advocacy efforts.  </strong></p>
<p>Shortly after establishing the AFSP chapter here, I was one of several people who pushed for the SB137 (Jason Flatt Act) in Alaska, under which all teachers are required to have annual suicide prevention training.  As a field ambassador, I write letters-to-the-editor of our local newspaper that gets sent to over 56 villages. I also stay in touch with Senator Murkowski, Senator Sullivan, and Representative Young about suicide prevention in rural Alaska.</p>
<p>Currently I am watching what happens to the Affordable Care Act. Cutting Medicaid would be a disaster for the native population. I would like to see more funding for mental health in rural Alaska. We need more clinicians to travel to the villages. I would like to see more school districts mandate suicide prevention training to all 6-12 graders. Young people talk to each other more than they do to their elders – we need them to be more aware of the warning signs for suicide.</p>
<p><strong>What are your hopes for the future, when it comes to suicide prevention in Alaska?  </strong></p>
<p>On average, there is a suicide every other day here. I would like to see no suicides.</p>
<p>I have been with AFSP for seven years now. Each year, the meaning of my work has grown. Joining AFSP has been like joining a family with one goal and mission. The advocacy work I do, and my close relationship with our state and federal officials, is vital to this mission.</p>
</div>
<i class="fa fa-times-circle ar17-close" aria-hidden="true"></i>
</div>

<h3>About State Capitol Days</h3>
<p>The annual <a href="http://afsp.org/our-work/advocacy/advocacy-events/state-capitol-days/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">AFSP State Capitol Days</a> bring advocates together to educate public officials about suicide prevention and discuss how legislators can help to reduce suicide in their states and communities. This year, State Capitol Day events were held in 32 states, up from 22 last year. Our voices are being heard: lawmakers passed and signed into law 13 state bills that AFSP had highlighted as top priorities at our State Capitol Day events.</p>
<p>This year, AFSP volunteers successfully advocated for passage of 4 new school suicide prevention laws.  A total of 27 states require suicide prevention training for school personnel, and now 15 states require school districts to have suicide prevention, intervention, and postvention policies in place.</p>
<p>In addition, AFSP volunteers successfully advocated for passage of 5 new laws increasing awareness of and access to suicide prevention and mental health resources on college and university campuses and 7 state bills to expand suicide prevention programming and crisis line access statewide.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>

<div class="right-panel">
<h3>Volunteer Spotlight</h3>
<h4>Patrick and Jackie Kimmel are Advocating for Smart Mental Health Policies in Pennsylvania</h4>
<img src="https://afsp.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/IMG_0662.jpg?w=1080" alt="">
<p>Patrick and Jackie Kimmel lost their young son Jacob to suicide in 2010. After attending one of AFSP’s <a href="https://afsp.org/find-support/ive-lost-someone/survivor-day/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Survivor Day</a> events, they decided to volunteer for their local chapter.</p>
<p>They have since gone on to co-chair their chapter’s advocacy committee, and have been instrumental in AFSP’s political advocacy work in Western Pennsylvania, making great strides this past year.</p>
<p><strong>What types of policies are you advocating for?</strong></p>
<p>We’re advocating for policies supporting mental health parity – meaning that mental health conditions should be covered in the same way as physical health conditions – and increased funding for suicide prevention.</p>
<p><strong>What kinds of things do you do to aid AFSP’s advocacy work? </strong></p>
<p>We have met with various legislators and their staff at the state and federal level to educate them about who AFSP is, <a href="https://afsp.org/our-work/advocacy/public-policy-priorities/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">the organization’s public policy priorities in preventing suicide</a>, what legislation AFSP supports in that effort, and how AFSP can help in their local community.</p>
<p>Locally throughout the Western Pennsylvania Chapter area, we and other chapter volunteers table at various community events such as mental health conferences, community walks, veteran’s forums, PRIDE Fest, and college fairs. Our objective is to inform the public about how fundraising provides money for research, education programs, political advocacy, and community support programs for mental health and suicide prevention.</p>
<p><img class="size-large wp-image-19586 aligncenter" src="http://afsp.imgix.net/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/FB_IMG_1460941491925-3.jpg?w=1024&amp;h=1024&amp;auto=format%2Cenhance" alt="" srcset="https://afsp.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/FB_IMG_1460941491925-3.jpg 640w, https://afsp.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/FB_IMG_1460941491925-3-300x225.jpg 300w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px" /></p>
<p><strong>What successes have you had?</strong></p>
<p>We have established political advocacy as one of the priorities for the Western Pennsylvania Chapter of AFSP. We have organized and scheduled legislative appointments during AFSP advocacy events in Harrisburg, Pennsylvania and Washington, D.C. for advocates throughout Pennsylvania to meet with representatives. As a result of traveling to Harrisburg, Pennsylvania and Washington, D.C. the last two years, we have developed a rapport with certain legislators and their staff.</p>
<p>We have also been fortunate to develop a collaborative relationship with state Representative Dan Miller from the 42nd Pennsylvania Legislative District. In April of 2016 we met with him on Pennsylvania <a href="https://afsp.org/our-work/advocacy/advocacy-events/state-capitol-days/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">State Capitol Day</a>. During our meeting he shared with us a bill he was in the process of writing that would require middle school students to have a depression screening along with other medical check-ups. Rep. Miller adjusted language in the proposal based on our input. We then put him in touch with AFSP’s Public Policy office in Washington D.C. to discuss his bill and how AFSP could provide support for its passage in Pennsylvania.</p>
<p>In March of this year, to help support Representative Miller’s depression screening bill, Patrick gave testimony before a fourteen member Pennsylvania congressional panel. In doing so, he shared our personal story of losing our son to suicide. Being open about these types of experiences has helped to make people realize how important the cause is, and that many, many people in our country have a personal connection to suicide.</p>
<p>We’ve also had the opportunity to talk about our advocacy work on local TV stations and newspapers, drawing attention to our cause. After one of these TV appearances, we were contacted by Pennsylvania Senator Pat Toomey’s legislative director, to congratulate us. This is important because it shows AFSP is becoming a recognized name in Washington D.C.</p>
<p><img class="size-large wp-image-19585 aligncenter" src="http://afsp.imgix.net/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/IMG_0348-1.jpg?w=1024&amp;h=1024&amp;auto=format%2Cenhance" alt="" srcset="https://afsp.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/IMG_0348-1.jpg 1920w, https://afsp.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/IMG_0348-1-300x200.jpg 300w, https://afsp.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/IMG_0348-1-768x512.jpg 768w, https://afsp.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/IMG_0348-1-1024x683.jpg 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 1920px) 100vw, 1920px" /></p>
<p><strong>What does your work with AFSP and suicide prevention advocacy represent to you, personally, in light of your loss?</strong></p>
<p>We believe that our passion, enthusiasm, and professionalism in pursuing advocacy for AFSP have been our greatest strengths. We’re not very technologically skilled, so we weren’t sure how much we could accomplish at first. But volunteering in this way has given us the opportunity to fight back against suicide, make a difference, and most importantly, honor our son, Jacob.</p>
</div>
<i class="fa fa-times-circle ar17-close" aria-hidden="true"></i>
</div>
<div class="story" id="isp_police">
<div class="left-panel">
<h3>About ISP</h3>
<p>Listed in the <a href="http://www.sprc.org/resources-programs/interactive-screening-program" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Best Practice Registry for Suicide Prevention</a>, the <a href="http://afsp.org/our-work/interactive-screening-program/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Interactive Screening Program (ISP)</a> is an online program being used by 110 college and university counseling centers, medical and professional degree schools, hospital networks, corporations and Employee Assistance Programs (EAPs), connecting thousands of people to help they would not have sought otherwise.</p>
</div>
<div class="right-panel">
<h3>Volunteer Spotlight</h3>
<h4>Working with Police to Curb Suicide Within the Ranks</h4>
<img src="https://afsp.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/Inside-brochure-1-Inside.jpg?w=1080" alt="">
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">In 2006, one of the officers who was a member of the Massachusetts Coalition of Police (<a href="https://www.masscop.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><span class="s2">MASS C.O.P.</span></a>) died by suicide. He was afraid to seek help because he didn’t want to lose his badge. </span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">This year, MASS C.O.P. President Scott Hovsepian announced that his union, which represents nearly 4,300 police officers in Massachusetts, would be instituting AFSP’s Interactive Screening Program, a Self-Check Quiz to reach distressed police officers and help connect them to peer support officers and mental health services before a crisis emerges. </span></p>
<p class="p3"><span class="s1">“If this can save one life, it is money, time, and energy well spent,” said Hovsepian, a 23 year police officer for the city of Waltham, MA. “You can’t put a price on a life. If we had had this program in place, we might not have lost our colleague to suicide in 2006. I want police officers nationwide to know that there are tools like the Self-Check Quiz that can help them through the hard times.</span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">AFSP’s Interactive Screening Program is used by institutions of higher education, workplaces, law enforcement agencies, and Employee Assistance Programs (EAPs) to reach distressed people and help connect them to mental health services before a crisis emerges.</span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">“We are honored to be partnering with MASS C.O.P. to offer the Self-Check Quiz to its members,” said Dr. Christine Moutier, AFSP chief medical officer. “Police officers are accustomed to servicing others, and this is a way for them to ensure they stay healthy and strong. Seeking help for your mental health is the brave thing to do.”</span></p>
</div>
<i class="fa fa-times-circle ar17-close" aria-hidden="true"></i>
</div>
<div class="story" id="phyllis_lgbtq">
<div class="left-panel">
<h3>About Stronger Communities: LGBTQ+ Suicide Prevention</h3>
<p><a href="https://afsp.org/our-work/education/stronger-communities-lgbtq-suicide-prevention/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Stronger Communities: LGBTQ+ Suicide Prevention</a> is a full-day conference sponsored by a local chapter of the American Foundation for Suicide Prevention. The goal is to raise awareness about LGBTQ+ suicide risk, bring research findings to the attention of professionals and the public, and explore strategies for LGBTQ+ suicide prevention in local communities. The agenda includes plenary and breakout sessions that feature national and local experts on LGBTQ+ mental health and suicide risk and will be focused on making mental health, suicide prevention, and education an LGBTQ+ community priority.</p>
</div>
<div class="right-panel">
<h3>Volunteer Spotlight</h3>
<h4>Making Suicide Prevention a Priority in the LGBTQ+ Community</h4>
<img src="https://afsp.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/LGBTQ-conference-1.jpg?w=1080" alt="">
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">This past April, AFSP’s Eastern Missouri Chapter hosted <i>Stronger Communities: </i></span><span class="s2"><i>LGBTQ+</i></span><span class="s1"><i> Suicide Prevention</i>, a day-long conference designed to raise awareness about LGBT suicide risk, share research findings, and explore strategies for LGBT suicide prevention in local communities. </span></p>
<p class="p2"><span class="s1">Phyllis Blackwelder, chair of the local AFSP chapter who organized the event, explains why she felt the conference was so important. </span></p>
<p class="p4"><span class="s1">“A few years ago, other AFSP volunteers and I started attending the local St. Louis Pride Festival. We set up a table featuring suicide prevention resources and information. I can’t begin to tell you how many people came up to us and said that AFSP was the reason they were still alive. It humbled me. This issue hit home for me personally at the time, because a friend of my step-daughter – a gay teenager not accepted by his family – had recently died by suicide. </span></p>
<p class="p4"><span class="s1">It also inspired us to provide more education to both local mental health professionals and residents in our area about topics related to the LGBTQ+ community. We decided to bring this event to St. Louis. </span></p>
<p class="p4"><span class="s1">The conference was a huge success. Local and national experts came and shared their expertise. We got a lot of personal notes from attendees thanking us and saying how much they had learned. </span></p>
<p class="p4"><span class="s1">There is a big need for this program right now, and it’s just one example of how AFSP’s education materials can be adapted for particular populations of people.”</span></p>
</div>
<i class="fa fa-times-circle ar17-close" aria-hidden="true"></i>

<div class="story" id="angela_real">
<div class="left-panel">
<h3>About It's Real</h3>
<div class="videoEmbed"><iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/YN69VIDKBFs" width="853" height="480" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen"></iframe></div>
<p><strong><span class="s2">Over 550 <i><a href="http://afsp.org/our-work/education/real-college-students-mental-health/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">It’s Real: College Students and Mental Health</a></i> videos were sold, and more than 20 free community presentations were held, in the first three months after its launch in April 2017.</span></strong></p>
<p><strong>More about It&#8217;s Real</strong></p>
<p>For many, college is a time of maturation, transition and growth, but can also come with great emotional challenge. This 17-minute film follows the journey of six students who wrestled with mental health concerns, sought treatment, made their psychological well-being a top priority, and found their own new sense of balance. The film has an accompanying five-minute expert commentary and a facilitator’s guide to support its use in educational programming. <span class="s2">The film is available as a <a href="https://store.afsp.org/afsp/product/C4A74790-9DF5-466C-A2C9-3C6F43C50EB3" target="_blank" rel="noopener">DVD</a> or in <a href="https://afsp.catalog.instructure.com/courses/realfilm" target="_blank" rel="noopener">digital download formats</a>, and includes a Facilitator Guide to help lead discussion</span></p>
</div>
<div class="right-panel">
<h3>Volunteer Spotlight</h3>
<h4>Angela M. Stowe & It’s Real at the University of Alabama at Birmingham</h4>
<img src="https://afsp.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/DT_uabstudentlife_3_677x380_FitToBoxSmallDimension_Center.jpg?w=1080" alt="">
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">Angela Stowe, Director of </span><span class="s2">Student Counseling Services and Wellness Promotion</span><span class="s1"> at the University of Alabama at Birmingham, oversaw the presentation of the AFSP-produced documentary <i>It’s Real: College Students and Mental Health</i> on her campus this past year. </span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1"><i>It’s Real</i> features the stories of six college students from across the country. Designed to raise awareness about mental health issues commonly experienced by students, the film is intended to be used as part of a school’s educational program to encourage help-seeking. </span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">By featuring real stories and experiences, the film conveys that depression and other mental health conditions are real illnesses that can be managed through specific treatments and interventions. It encourages students to be mindful of the state of their mental health, to acknowledge and recognize when they are struggling, and to take steps to seek help.</span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">“College students face significant challenges around anxiety, loneliness, isolation, relationships, and just life management in general. They also have a significant amount of trauma, we’ve seen.</span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">We’ve trained over 200 students, faculty and staff since July. The film has been a terrific conversation starter and a really wonderful way to frame the discussion about suicide and our college students. Those who attend leave with a better understanding of how to recognize, understand and support students who may be at risk for suicide.”</span></p>
</div>
<i class="fa fa-times-circle ar17-close" aria-hidden="true"></i>
</div>
<div class="story" id="nypd_tsl">
<div class="left-panel">
<h3>About Talk Saves Lives™</h3>
<div class="videoEmbed"><iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/WFVVwLERoX4?rel=0" width="560" height="315" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen" data-mce-fragment="1"></iframe></div>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1"><i>Talk Saves Lives™: An Introduction to Suicide Prevention</i> is a free community-based presentation that covers the general scope of suicide, the research on prevention, and what people can do to fight suicide. Attendees learn what suicide is; who it affects; what we know about it; the risk and warning signs of suicide; and how together, we can help prevent it.</span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">Since TSL launched</span><span class="s1">, the program has reach more than </span><span class="s3">33,000</span><span class="s1"> people. </span><span class="s1">Special modules of Talk Saves Lives<i>™</i> have been made available to help us reach special </span><span class="s3">populations, such as Seniors, LGBTQ+ individuals, and firearms owners.</span></p>
</div>
<div class="right-panel">
<h3>Volunteer Spotlight</h3>
<h4>Talk Saves Lives™ and the New York Police Department</h4>
<img src="https://afsp.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/image010.jpg?w=1080" alt="">
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">Both AFSP and The NYPD are dedicated to helping people in crisis. This past year, AFSP collaborated with the New York Police Department on a number of initiatives, all designed to keep people safe, including AFSP’s educational program, <i>Talk Saves Lives™: An Introduction to Suicide Prevention</i>. </span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">Detective Jeff Thompson, NYPD, Strategic and Crisis Communication, was involved with this growing partnership from the very beginning, and as it continues to expand. </span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1"><b>How did the NYPD’s collaboration with AFSP come about? Had you noticed a specific need?</b></span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">The connection first started when the NYPD created a Twitter account &#8212; @TalkToMe &#8212; to help share information on mental illness, share crisis communication skills, and connect people with services. We then wanted to connect with the suicide prevention and mental health community for further expertise. AFSP was our first stop!</span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1"><b>Are there any special considerations regarding mental health and suicide prevention for police?</b></span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">Often, police officers get called when the situation is tense, emotionally driven, unpredictable, and potentially violent. We are there to help the person, and it can be very complicated, because the person does not always realize that.</span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">For someone who is despondent or potentially suicidal, we are there when they may be having the worst moment of their life. Based on the elite training our officers get, we try to dispel the person’s feelings of being alone, that the situation is hopeless, and that there are no options. The officers’ approach is grounded in using active listening skills to slow the situation down, de-escalate tense and negative emotions, demonstrate empathy, and build rapport in order achieve a peaceful resolution.</span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1"><b>What exactly has the collaboration consisted of? </b></span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">The work between the NYPD and the AFSP consists of various collaborations. It started with social media and progressed to many other in-person activities. This includes someone from AFSP’s New York chapter speaking at precinct roll-calls to address officers just prior to going out on patrol; creating joint public service announcements that have been used locally and nationally; and developing handout material for officers to provide them with tips on what to say (and avoid saying) when engaging a suicidal person.</span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">AFSP’s <i>Talk Saves Lives™ </i>has been presented at numerous local, precinct-level community council meetings where guest speakers are often invited. This provided a perfect partnership between the NYPD and AFSP. Special handouts were provided to the attendees so they would have even more information at their fingertips.</span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">Recently, AFSP has also been providing insight on an NYPD internal project that seeks to reduce police officer suicide. Dr. Christine Moutier, AFSP’s Chief Medical Officer, has also filmed a pair of videos for the law enforcement audience with the NYPD. The practical guidance provided by AFSP has helped ensure that NYPD outreach is conducted effectively and based on best practices.</span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">We look forward to continuing and expanding our collaboration, and are more than willing to connect and share this with other police departments across the country.</span></p>
<p><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-19636" src="http://afsp.imgix.net/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/3e028b9.jpg?w=1024&amp;h=1024&amp;auto=format%2Cenhance" alt="" srcset="https://afsp.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/3e028b9.jpg 368w, https://afsp.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/3e028b9-150x150.jpg 150w, https://afsp.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/3e028b9-300x300.jpg 300w" sizes="(max-width: 368px) 100vw, 368px" /></p>
</div>
<i class="fa fa-times-circle ar17-close" aria-hidden="true"></i>
</div>
<div class="story" id="lamas_tsl">
<div class="left-panel">
<h3>About Talk Saves Lives™</h3>
<div class="videoEmbed"><iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/WFVVwLERoX4?rel=0" width="560" height="315" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen"></iframe></div>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1"><i>Talk Saves Lives™: An Introduction to Suicide Prevention</i> is a free community-based presentation that covers the general scope of suicide, the research on prevention, and what people can do to fight suicide. Attendees learn what suicide is; who it affects; what we know about it; the risk and warning signs of suicide; and how together, we can help prevent it.</span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">Since TSL launched</span><span class="s1">, the program has reach more than </span><span class="s3">33,000</span><span class="s1"> people. </span><span class="s1">Special modules of Talk Saves Lives<i>™</i> have been made available to help us reach special </span><span class="s3">populations, such as Seniors, LGBTQ+ individuals, and firearms owners.</span></p>
</div>
<div class="right-panel">
<h3>Volunteer Spotlight</h3>
<h4>Denisse Lamas delivers Talk Saves Lives™ in Spanish</h4>
<img src="https://afsp.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/AAEAAQAAAAAAAAJlAAAAJDVmZWNlYmFmLTIyZGItNDAzYy1hYjJkLTI3YTQ1NTk4ZjZhYQ.jpg?w=1080" alt="">
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">Denisse Lamas is a licensed clinical social worker who has volunteered with AFSP’s Central Florida Chapter since 2009. This past year, in an effort to reach Florida’s </span><span class="s2">Hispanic</span><span class="s1"> population and bring much needed suicide prevention training to the community, she began presenting AFSP’s educational program <i>Talk Saves Lives</i>™ in Spanish. </span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1"><b>How did you first get involved at AFSP?</b></span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">I was the Suicide Prevention counselor for Orange County Public Schools. One of the founding members of AFSP’s Central Florida chapter reached out to me about attending chapter board meetings so that we could learn from each other. At that moment, I realized the huge stigma associated with suicide and I wanted to do something about it.</span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1"><b>Had you noticed a specific need for this program?</b></span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">Yes. </span><span class="s2">Hispanics</span><span class="s1"> are one of the largest and fastest growing populations in Central Florida and there is also a large stigma surrounding mental health and suicide in the Hispanic population. I’ve been especially focused on providing mental health education to Florida’s Hispanic population in the aftermath of the PULSE night club shooting in Orlando. </span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1"><b>Are there any special considerations regarding mental health and suicide prevention for the Spanish-speaking audience?</b></span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">Cultural competency is important. All Hispanics/ Latinos have different cultures that play a role in their upbringing. Spanish is spoken differently in different countries and the same word may have different meanings in different countries. It’s great to be able to offer AFSP’s <i>Talk Saves Lives</i>™ program not just in Spanish, but weaving these important cultural considerations into the presentation. </span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1"><b>Were there any particular challenges in arranging for the program?</b></span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">I was concerned about attendance, because people – especially in this community – are not accustomed to openly talking about these topics. However, there are people who realize they need this training, both for themselves and to help others recognize <a href="https://afsp.org/about-suicide/risk-factors-and-warning-signs/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><span class="s3">common warning signs</span></a> and become aware of practical ways to prevent suicide. We held the<b> </b><i>Talk Saves Lives</i>™ program on several occasions in both English and in Spanish, and to my surprise, the Spanish version was more attended than the English version! </span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1"><b>How did it go? </b></span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">People asked so many questions that I learned to expect an active Q&amp;A session! This shows how hungry people are for suicide prevention education. It all went so well that I was able to provide the program not only in Central Florida, but in Rhode Island and Puerto Rico. </span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1"><b>What are your hopes for building on this success in the future? </b></span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">Every time I offer this program, more people attend! I have also now been invited to offer the Talk Saves Lives program in churches, which is another environment in which I hope to encourage more openness about the topic of suicide prevention and mental health.</span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">I hope that <i>Talk Saves Lives</i>™ is presented more frequently in Spanish and that we can continue to reach more and more people.</span></p>
</div>
<i class="fa fa-times-circle ar17-close" aria-hidden="true"></i>
</div>
<div class="story" id="heraldo_walks">
<div class="left-panel">
<h3>About Out of the Darkness Community Walks</h3>
<div class="videoEmbed"><iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/zmjmr1pt3KE?rel=0" width="560" height="315" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen"></iframe></div>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">Many people affected by suicide first learn of AFSP through the Out of the Darkness Walks. When the walks first began in 2004, few people attended.</span><strong><span class="s1"> This year, over 260,000 people participated in </span><span class="s2">over 550 </span><span class="s1">walks across the country. </span></strong></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">The Out of the Darkness Walks are AFSP’s largest fundraising effort, and this year was no exception, with over $22 million raised for research, education, advocacy, and support programs.</span></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">The core of the Out of the Darkness Walks, the Community Walks created a movement. Held in hundreds of cities across the country, they give people the courage to open up about their own struggle or loss, and the platform to change our culture’s approach to mental health. This year we held over 400 walks, covering all 50 states and raised $</span><span class="s1">17.5M with more than 280,000 individuals walking or donating to the cause.</span></p>
<p class="p1">
</div>
<div class="right-panel">
<h3>Volunteer Spotlight</h3>
<h4>Walking Out of the Darkness in the Bay Area</h4>
<img src="https://afsp.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/IMG_6255.jpg?w=1080" alt="">
<p>Sarah Heraldo first began volunteering for AFSP as a college student, despite having no direct connection to suicide. She has helped organize Out of the Darkness Community Walks in the Bay Area for the last several years.</p>
<p><strong>How did you first get involved with AFSP?</strong></p>
<p>I first got involved with the AFSP through volunteering for the San Francisco Out of the Darkness Walk. My fiancé, Robin Lopez, attended the walks for years and even spoke at the Overnight in 2012 after the death of his best friend, Mark. Robin and I were both actively involved in a community service organization on our college campus. He reached out to his local AFSP chapter to ask if some of our college friends could volunteer for the walk. That was how I first became involved with AFSP. I have no direct connection to suicide, but its impact on my loved ones has definitely changed my own life.</p>
<p><strong>In what ways have you been involved over the years?</strong></p>
<p>I took the opportunity to create an Out of the Darkness Walks Committee within our campus organization. My main goal was to reach college students and educate them about suicide prevention and work together to erase the stigma that sometimes still exists around mental health. We arranged a speaker through AFSP, and hosted a Talk Saves Lives™ event, which over 70 students attended!</p>
<p><img class="size-large wp-image-19559 aligncenter" src="http://afsp.imgix.net/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/DSC06289.jpg?w=1024&amp;h=1024&amp;auto=format%2Cenhance" alt="" srcset="https://afsp.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/DSC06289.jpg 6000w, https://afsp.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/DSC06289-300x200.jpg 300w, https://afsp.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/DSC06289-768x512.jpg 768w, https://afsp.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/DSC06289-1024x683.jpg 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 6000px) 100vw, 6000px" /></p>
<p><strong>What have you been up to this year?</strong></p>
<p>After graduating college, I moved back to San Jose, my hometown, and joined the South Bay Out of the Darkness Walks Committee. I’m particularly interested in reaching a younger demographic of people – particularly students in elementary, middle school, high school, and college. On the committee, I act as Outreach Coordinator and Walk Day Lead, working directly with volunteers along the walk route, giving them specific instructions, whether it’s cheering walkers on at specific points, or directing them along the walk route.</p>
<p><strong>What does your work with AFSP mean to you, personally?</strong></p>
<p>Although I have no direct connection to suicide, personally, suicide has affected my loved ones. It brings me sadness, but there is also joy in knowing there are organizations like AFSP that raise awareness and provide support and education. It’s a blessing to know there are others out there who understand and – literally, in the case of the Out of the Darkness Walks – stand in solidarity for the cause.</p>
<p><strong>What changes in the world would you like to see as a result of your activities, particularly with the Walks? </strong></p>
<p>My primary career goal is to spread education about mental health and suicide prevention. In addition to staying involved in the walks, <span class="s1">I’d like to help bring AFSP’s education programs to schools,</span> because mental health is something that needs to be addressed early and dealt with head on.</p>
<p>My main goal with the Community Walks is to let people know there are people out where who know what others are going through, and working to reduce the suicide rate.</p>
</div>
<i class="fa fa-times-circle ar17-close" aria-hidden="true"></i>
</div>

<p>The Fargo Ride to Fight Suicide was only one of many motorcycle rides held by AFSP chapters nationwide every year. Last year over 360 bikers participated in 11 rides, each contributing their voices to support research and education that saves lives. You can help the movement continue to grow by <a href="https://afsp.donordrive.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=donorDrive.eventList&amp;eventType=P,T&amp;eventGroupID=9AA1FFD9-F204-0EA0-86A84C4FE272F2F3" target="_blank" rel="noopener">signing up for an event near you today</a>.</p>
